observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Municipal Mayor together with the other offices concerned agreed to implement the following courses of actions:
The requisitioning offices ensure timely submission of RIS to the MTO/GSO for the preparation of the SSMI to be submitted to the Municipal Accountant to provide a basis in computing the cost of supplies and ending inventory, as well as recording the expenditures using appropriate expenditure accounts;
The Inventory Committee in coordination with the MTO/GSO conduct the physical count of inventories at least every six months and prepare the RPCI for the inventory counted to ensure that reliable inventory balances are established, which can be verified in terms of existence, conditions, and accountability;
The Municipal Mayor consider the establishment of the General Service Office to ease the workload of the MTO, allowing it to focus on managing the LGU’s funds and supervising treasury operations without compromising the effectiveness and efficiency of both functions; and
The Municipal Accounting Office recognize prior period adjustment account, for the inventory issued in previous year following the proposed adjusting journal entries (PAJE) as shown below:

We recommended and the:
MTO/GSO agreed to prepare PCs for every class of PPE to record the acquisition, description, custody, disposal, and other information about the fixed asset, so that they can be used as a source document in conducting reconciliation with the records of the Accounting Office;
Municipal Accounting Office agreed to prepare RPLC in the prescribed format in accordance with MNGAS to document all the necessary details of PPE, so that they can be used as source documents in conducting reconciliation with the records of the MTO/GSO;
Inventory Committee agreed to undertake the one-time cleansing of PPE and adhere to the stated guidelines and procedures of COA Circular 2020-006 to ensure that reliable PPE balances are established, which can be verified in terms of existence, conditions, and accountability; and
Municipal Mayor or his authorized representative agreed to consider establishing the General Services Office to relieve the MTO of the responsibility for supply and property management and to better manage the increasing number of PPEs in the Municipality.

